<TITLE> Hasina urges allies to work together </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, June 1 (bdnews24.com)  Prime minister Sheikh Hasina has urged members of the alliance government to unite and work together for realising the expectations of the people. Hasina made the call in a meeting on Thursday to the 'grand alliance' that participated in the last national election under one banner. She said that people have confidence over the government that came to power with a landslide victory in the ninth parliamentary elections. Also president of the ruling Awami League, Hasina said that the 14-party grand alliance had fought to establish people's rights. "Now we have to work together to meet their expectations." "I believe that we can work for people's socio-economic development if we work together," Hasina said. AL presidium members Syeda Sajeda Chowdhury, party general secretary Syed Ashraful Islam, Worker's Party president Rashed Khan Menon, Sharif Nurul Ambia of Jatiya Shomajtantrik Dal, Wazedul Islam Khan of Communist Kendra, Zakir Hossain of Ganatantrik Majdur Party, Hazi Abdus Samad of Gana Azadi League, Misbahur Rahman Chowdhury of Islami Oikkya Jote and chief whip Abdus Shahid were on the dais with Hasina. In the beginning of her speech, the AL chief said that the meeting was organised to greet everyone at the Ganabhaban, official residence of the prime minister. Hasina said, "We want a democratic culture to be established in the country so that the people's representatives can run the affairs of the country." "We have achieved democracy despite many hurdles. Now we want to drive the country through the right path." "Our aim is to meet the pledges of the people," she added. With a view to strengthening local government, the prime minister said that development work would increase in the rural areas, not only in the urban areas. "Buying capacity of those people has to be increased too." "We must revitalise the rural economy," she stressed. Referring to the changes made in the education system with the approval of a new education policy, Hasina said, "We have the desire but not always the means." She also mentioned formulation of a trust fund to offer scholarships to students up till university so that they could study free of cost. The AL chief also asked the parliament members from her party and the grand alliance to prepare for the upcoming budget session. At the end of the meeting, Musa Ibrahim, the first Bangladeshi to reach the highest peak of Everest, joined a dinner at the Ganabhaban. The prime minister greeted him for the extraordinary feat. bd
